Example of Unbalanced Repeated Measures Mixed-Model

First, lets import the dataset 

bears <- read.csv("~/Desktop/Analytics/mixed_effects_practice/mixed_effects_practice/data/all_bears.csv")
bears$name <- as.factor(bears$name) #make bear ID a factor

Next, lets plot it to visualize the dataset 

ggplot(bears, aes(x=season, y=dist, group=name, color=name, shape=name)) + 
  geom_point(size=4, position = position_dodge2(width=.33, preserve = "total")) +
  #geom_line() +
  geom_smooth(method = "lm", se = FALSE) +
  labs(title="Seasonal Distance Traveled by Bears", x= "season", y = "distance")
## `geom_smooth()` using formula 'y ~ x'

Calculate the mean distance for each season

bears_means <- bears %>%
  group_by(season) %>%
  summarise(mean_rating=mean(dist),
            se_rating=sd(dist)/sqrt(n()))
bears_means
## # A tibble: 4 x 3
##   season mean_rating se_rating
##   <chr>        <dbl>     <dbl>
## 1 I             532.      83.3
## 2 II           1109.      99.1
## 3 III          1215.     120. 
## 4 IV           1566.     162.

Run anova of model 

mixed_bears <- lmer(dist~(season*name)+(1|name), data = bears)
## Warning: Model failed to converge with 1 negative eigenvalue: -1.3e-06
anova(mixed_bears)

Check the overall performance of the model 

performance::check_model(mixed_bears)

calculate model-adjusted means (e.g.estimated marginal means) 

mixed_bears_emm <- emmeans(mixed_bears, "season")

Compare raw means to model-adjusted means (emmeans) 

ggplot(data_emm, aes(x=season, y=emmean)) + 
  geom_point(size=4) +
  geom_errorbar(aes(ymin=emmean-SE, ymax=emmean+SE), width=.2) +
  labs(title="help", x= "Season", y = "Distance") +
  geom_point(data=bears_means, size=4, x=bears_means$season, y=bears_means$mean_rating, color="blue")

Pretty close!

Example of Hierarchical Nested Design Mixed-Effects Model

Sailfin Mollies (left) and the Everglades in Florida, United States (right).

To begin, lets import the dataset 

herb_data<- read.csv("~/Desktop/Analytics/mixed_effects_practice/mixed_effects_practice/data/herb_data.csv")

Now, lets visualize the data 

ggplot(herb_data, aes(treatment, fish_survival, colour = as.factor(tank), shape=as.factor(measurement))) + 
  geom_jitter(width =0.15, size=5)+
  xlab ("Treatment Type") +
  ylab ("Survivability of Fish") +
  labs(title="Influence of Treatment Type on Survivability of Sailfin Mollies")

Note that the echo = FALSE parameter was added to the code chunk to prevent printing of the R code that generated the plot.

herb.1 <- lmer(fish_survival ~ (1|treatment/tank), data =herb_data)
## boundary (singular) fit: see ?isSingular
summary(herb.1)
## Linear mixed model fit by REML. t-tests use Satterthwaite's method [
## lmerModLmerTest]
## Formula: fish_survival ~ (1 | treatment/tank)
##    Data: herb_data
## 
## REML criterion at convergence: -51.4
## 
## Scaled residuals: 
##     Min      1Q  Median      3Q     Max 
## -3.0839 -0.5566  0.1832  0.3902  2.0246

##  treatment      (Intercept) 0.004027 0.06346

## Number of obs: 24, groups:  tank:treatment, 12; treatment, 4

## (Intercept)  0.92020    0.03441 3.00000   26.74 0.000115 ***

anova(lm(fish_survival ~ treatment/tank, data = herb_data))
## Analysis of Variance Table
## 
## Response: fish_survival
##                Df   Sum Sq   Mean Sq F value   Pr(>F)

## ---
## Signif. codes:  0 '***' 0.001 '**' 0.01 '*' 0.05 '.' 0.1 ' ' 1
herb.2 <- lmer(fish_survival ~ treatment + (1|treatment/tank), data = herb_data)
## boundary (singular) fit: see ?isSingular
## Warning in as_lmerModLT(model, devfun): Model may not have converged with 1
## eigenvalue close to zero: -1.0e-10
anova(herb.2)
## Type III Analysis of Variance Table with Satterthwaite's method
##             Sum Sq   Mean Sq NumDF DenDF F value Pr(>F)
## treatment 0.010747 0.0035823     3    20  0.8414 0.4872
anova(herb.2,herb.1, test = "Chisq")
